Teamwork

Culture of Humility

Wildcard Questions

Afterward, my brother taught me programming languages like Python and Java, which allowed me to express myself beyond words. Alongside this passion for technology was my desire to understand patternsâ€”what made systems function and how information flowed. Even at eight, I noticed my tendency to question perspectives and reimagine realities, and this curiosity naturally extended to storytelling. The more I learned, the more I saw the connection between technology and how stories are told. As a math and computer science major, my career goal is to use technology to enhance storytellingâ€”creating interactive platforms that bring narratives to life, preserve cultural histories, and make information immersive. Through data visualization, augmented reality, and interactive media, I look forward to building tools that allow for adaptive storytelling.

[7/23/25, 12:30:10â€¯PM] SisturrrğŸ¤¡ğŸ¦: Question: Tell us how to prioritize the advancements in STEM over the next decade and how women can lead or contribute significantly to these changes. Our scholarship committee prioritizes applications that provide supporting examples and evidence of impact. 


â€œIf more people were affected, there would already be a solution.â€

Lotanna and I were catching up over FaceTime, talking loosely about the next ten yearsâ€”marriage, children, and careers. We are two Black immigrant women in our mid-20s; she just finished her masterâ€™s, and Iâ€™m starting mine in nursing this fall at Johns Hopkins. As we laughed about balancing ambition with childcare, we paused to reflect on the alarming maternal mortality statistics for Black women. Thatâ€™s when I said it: "If more people were affected, there would already be a solution."

We could discuss numerous crises in maternal health: postpartum depression often going undiagnosed, women having to choose between childcare and careers, medical gaslighting during pregnancy, and the unaffordability of maternity leave. All of these issues highlight a broken system that urgently needs reform. However, at the core of this system is the harsh reality that pregnancy, particularly for Black women, can be a deadly undertaking.

According to the most recent National Vital Statistics System (NVSS) data from 2023, maternal deaths in the U.S. dropped from 817 in 2022 to 669 in 2023. Still, Black women are dying at over three times the rate of White women. In 2023, for every 100,000 live births, 50.3 Black women died compared to 14.5 White women, 12.4 Hispanic women, and 10.7 Asian American women.

In light of these statistics, I propose that over the next decade, STEM advancements should focus on overhauling the maternal healthcare system as a matter of justice and survival. To achieve this, we must first ensure that every clinical trial for maternal-health devices and protocols includes representative samples of Black women to close the data gap that has marginalized us in healthcare. Next, we should capitalize on the era of artificial intelligence by incorporating AI-powered devices into maternal healthcare, allowing us to identify potential issues in high-risk pregnancies before they escalate. We must also extend these AI technologies to postpartum care by creating affordable and user-friendly wearable sensors that monitor vital signs and notify users of any potential emergencies or unusual changes after birth. In conjunction with these devices, we need telehealth platforms that connect new mothers to trauma-informed and culturally competent care at any point in their pregnancy journey, whether before, during, or after.

Additionally, federal and private funding agencies must tie grants to diversity mandates in biotech and data science projects to ensure that innovations aimed at improving pregnancy and birth reflect and serve everyone, especially the most at-risk women. Finally, STEM employers must support innovators by implementing family-friendly policies, flexible schedules, and work environments that recognize caregiving as part of life rather than a detour from it.

Women, especially Black women, are uniquely qualified to lead these initiatives. Our lived experiences help us identify the blind spots that science often overlooks. In our careers as nurses, engineers, data scientists, policy advocates, and entrepreneurs, we can drive this transformation. And we already are.

As clinical researchers, we will redesign clinical trials to accurately reflect the complete spectrum of the birthing population, building on Dr. Elizabeth Howellâ€™s work at Mount Sinai, which highlighted racial disparities in severe maternal morbidity. As technology leaders, we will expand platforms like Dr. Stacy Lindauâ€™s NowPow, which uses brief patient questionnaires and diagnosis codes to identify the needs of new mothers, such as food, housing, or mental health support, and connect them to nearby, culturally sensitive resources; demonstrating that timely, culturally informed referrals can save lives. As engineers working with healthcare providers, we can prototype and pilot postpartum technologies that are practical and accessible: affordable wearables, at-home testing kits, and telehealth apps that empower women to take charge of their health. As policymakers and advocates, we can author and defend equity-tied funding mandates like Rep. Lauren Underwoodâ€™s Momnibus Act, which allocated over $200 million for community-based maternal programs. And as leaders in our labs and workplaces, we can implement trauma-informed, family-friendly policies such as flexible schedules, paid leave, and mental health support, to ensure mothers thrive in STEM careers, so that women like Lotanna and me, who desire both fulfilling motherhood and impactful careers in healthcare, aren't forced to choose between the two. We must not wait for more people to be affected before creating lasting solutions.

This fall, Iâ€™ll step into Johns Hopkins as a nursing student, bringing these conversations into every classroom, every ward, and every clinic, because for women like me, improving this system remains my daily commitment.

I have immense pleasure to write this letter of recommendation for Ahunna Ike-Njoku in support of her application for IIE scholarship. In a short time since agreeing to mentor Ahunna, I have had the opportunity to witness her exceptional academic, professional and leadership qualities firsthand. As a Hackathon and TMCF Immersion Scholar,
Ahunna has persistently demonstrated remarkable analytical skills, strategic thinking, and
leadership abilities that sets her apart. One notable example of her problem solving capabilities
was when she led a cross-functional team of 5 young adults to design Nativa, a culturally smart food access app for some underserved communities around her college.

Ahunna's ability to navigate complex situations, collaborate effectively with diverse teams, and drive results emphasizes her readiness for a rigorous engineering career that will be of benefits to underrepresented groups in our society.

Beyond technical expertise, Ahunna is an outstanding team player and a natural leader. She has mentored fellow interns, fostered a culture of innovation, and taken initiative in high-pressure situations. Her strong communication skills and ability to build relationships make her highly efficient in both academic and professional setting.

I have no doubt that Ahunna will bring the same level of commitment, passion, and strategic insight to programs that are dedicated to promote women participation in engineering education. I strongly recommend her for this scholarship

[9/14/25, 6:03:04â€¯AM] Ahunna Theresaâ¤ï¸: When my children were very little, they also didn't know good and bad, or at the very least didn't understand the difference. I have many electric devices in my home that can be used for good or bad. And plenty of non electric devices, like knives and my fireplace. My children didn't understand that. I simply told them not to play with the outlets or the stove because they could get hurt or die. They trusted me, just as Adam and Eve should have trusted God. But if someone came over to my home and showed only one side of how electricity or fire works and not the other, deceiving my children to disobey, my young child would have gotten hurt. The tree most likely provided shade, a good thing, but the fruit was not good to eat, just like many plants today are not safe for humans to eat. Now I know that some people think, but you're not God. You aren't omniscient. I'm certainly glad for that. But God gave mankind free will, for without free will, we cannot love willingly. So yes, He could have not created the tree in the first place. But then, where was the freedom to choose. 
I understand that there's a movement to attempt to deconstruct Christianity, especially in America, but in order to deconstruct something, you have to know how it's constructed in the first place. Otherwise, you just end up with strawmen, and non sequiturs, equivocations, and appeals to emotion.

[2/4/26, 7:33:44â€¯PM] Ahunna Theresaâ¤ï¸: Growing up in a family that owned very little, I watched scarcity shape my parents' every decision, dictating which needs were met and which were postponed. Beyond our home, the businesses in my neighborhood faced similar trade-offs, often lowering their product quality to stay afloat.
This early exposure to lack shaped my career goal to help companies maximize their financial capacity and, in turn, the reach of their social impact. I knew what it meant to desperately wish, for instance, that the water factories we relied on could afford to meet basic hygiene standards.

Through my degree in Applied Analytics at Columbia University, I hope to better understand and analyze the financial decisions that shape what companies are able to offer the communities they serve. This scholarship would allow me to pursue this training with focus and intention, building technical fluency in modeling, inference, and data interpretation that I can carry directly into roles within financial services.

[5/17/25, 3:38:44â€¯AM] GraceeğŸ’“ğŸ’“ğŸ¥°: For me, one of the key things I do by God's grace to have a productive day is to *write down everything I plan to do that day.* 

It could be in form of a to-do list where I get to tick the boxes once I'm done with a particular task. Or I just write them out and strike as I complete each task. 

It helps me a lot because once I tick a particular box or strike out a task, it comes with a feeling of accomplishment that makes me want to complete the rest. Having everything struck out or ticked is usually the highlight, because somehow, the energy enters into the next day. 

And one truth is, you won't always complete your daily tasks â€” and that's okay. Because everyday won't be the same. There are days you complete all and others you complete only a few or even barely struggle to complete one. On such days, no need to beat yourself up. Maybe it's an indication that you've been pushing yourself too hard and your body needs a break. Rest and continue. 

What matters is not in perfection, but in the ability to get things done. At least, you show up daily and it's something to be proud of. 

My two cents. â€<This message was edited>

[11/30/25, 10:02:38â€¯PM] johnğŸ˜: Good afternoon Alia,

Following the conversion we had, I know you've been through a lot, and I'm not disputing that. The death of your mom and many other things have affected you deeply. It's normal to feel that way, and I would probably think the same if I were in your shoes. However, I want to remind you that God is still God, despite everything that happened. He's been faithful in the past, and He's still faithful.

If all you draw from your mom's death is that God doesn't exist, then the devil has a loophole to penetrate your life. But I want you to know that there's more to life than the pain you're going through. When you receive Christ, you'll have access to God, and that's when things will start to change. You'll have the comfort to stand up and tell the devil that you won't give up.

Life is more spiritual, and we either belong to God or the devil. If you keep believing and thinking that life has no purpose without God, you're giving the devil an opportunity to take control of your life. That's when depression and other issues can set in, leaving you feeling empty despite your achievements. You might feel a vacuum inside, and it's hard to shake off. But I'm telling you, when you come to Christ and acknowledge Him, He'll help you deal with those things. Christ will treat those wounds and bring healing to your life.

Don't let pain define you; instead, use it as an opportunity to draw closer to God. Just like Job, who remained faithful despite his pain, you can too. Your mom didn't live a wasted life; she lived an impactful life, raising children who'll impact others. She loved you more than anyone else, and that's why she's giving you advice. Keep her legacy going, and live a life that makes an impact.

I believe God will use you mightily for His work. Think about these things, read this message well, and let it sink in.

If you have any questions feel free to reach out

[11/30/25, 10:02:38â€¯PM] johnğŸ˜: Good afternoon Alia,

Following the conversion we had, I know you've been through a lot, and I'm not disputing that. The death of your mom and many other things have affected you deeply. It's normal to feel that way, and I would probably think the same if I were in your shoes. However, I want to remind you that God is still God, despite everything that happened. He's been faithful in the past, and He's still faithful.

If all you draw from your mom's death is that God doesn't exist, then the devil has a loophole to penetrate your life. But I want you to know that there's more to life than the pain you're going through. When you receive Christ, you'll have access to God, and that's when things will start to change. You'll have the comfort to stand up and tell the devil that you won't give up.

Life is more spiritual, and we either belong to God or the devil. If you keep believing and thinking that life has no purpose without God, you're giving the devil an opportunity to take control of your life. That's when depression and other issues can set in, leaving you feeling empty despite your achievements. You might feel a vacuum inside, and it's hard to shake off. But I'm telling you, when you come to Christ and acknowledge Him, He'll help you deal with those things. Christ will treat those wounds and bring healing to your life.

Don't let pain define you; instead, use it as an opportunity to draw closer to God. Just like Job, who remained faithful despite his pain, you can too. Your mom didn't live a wasted life; she lived an impactful life, raising children who'll impact others. She loved you more than anyone else, and that's why she's giving you advice. Keep her legacy going, and live a life that makes an impact.

I believe God will use you mightily for His work. Think about these things, read this message well, and let it sink in.

If you have any questions feel free to reach out

[1/13/26, 3:26:25â€¯PM] Ahunna Theresaâ¤ï¸: Automatic Visa Revalidation (AVR) lets certain nonimmigrant visa holders (like F-1, J-1, H-1B) re-enter the U.S. with an expired visa after short trips (â‰¤30 days) to Canada, Mexico, or adjacent islands, using their valid I-94 record and maintaining status, but it excludes travelers from designated countries (Iran, Syria, etc.) or those with denied visa applications. AVR essentially "extends" the expired visa for the trip, allowing for seamless reentry without a new visa stamp if rules are followed. 
Who Qualifies (Generally)

Status Holders: F-1 (Students), J-1 (Exchange Visitors), H-1B (Specialty Occupations), O (Extraordinary Ability), etc..
Valid I-94: Must have a current, unexpired I-94 record (DHS admission stamp).
Short Trips: Travel to Canada, Mexico, or Caribbean "adjacent islands" for 30 days or less.

Where You Can Go
Canada & Mexico: The primary destinations.
Adjacent Islands: Bahamas, Barbados, Bermuda, Dominican Republic, Haiti, Jamaica, Martinique, St. Pierre & Miquelon, Trinidad, and certain Leeward/Windward Islands. 

Key Rules & Requirements
Valid Passport: Your passport must be valid.
Valid I-94: Essential for proving current legal status.
Status Maintained: You must intend to resume your original nonimmigrant status.
Expired Visa OK: An expired visa stamp is treated as valid for return.

[2/28/25, 3:39:02â€¯PM] Eunice FedacadğŸ‰: SHOULD FEMALE BELIEVERS WEAR TROUSERS? 

Evangelist Gloria Bamiloye answersâ€¦

Deuteronomy 22:5 KJVS
[5] The woman shall not wear that which pertaineth unto a man, neither shall a man put on a womanâ€™s garment: for all that do so are abomination unto the Lord thy God.

The scripture does not specify the cloths for the man and the one for the woman from this verse. And so it depends on what each country ,nations ,Tribe accepts as the cloth for the man or for woman

For example in our country Nigeria ,there are so many tribes and tongues not to talk about the world. This scripture therefore does not specify but the Lord expect us to now walk with our initiatives on how a child of God should dress based on where he or she comes from.

In the western world, Men and women wear trousers. Women have her own special way of sewing their trousers and the same with men.

In Africa, we have some who wear trousers while majority donâ€™t.

Now coming down to our country, in yoruba land, culturally, ladies donâ€™t wear trousers while men wear. In some parts of Nigeria, in some tribes, men tie wrapper like women
Because of these varieties in tribes and culture all over the world it is difficult to say this is how somebody should dress. In Scotland for example, men wear skirt like women.
1 Corinthians 8:9 KJVS
[9] But take heed lest by any means this liberty of yours become a stumbling block to them that are weak.

Even though we have liberty to put on whatever we feel like wearing, we must not become stumbling block for others who are weak. That is to say according to Paul if ordinary eating of meat will course your brother to stumble away from faith ,he said he will not eat meat again

1 Corinthians 8:11-13 KJVS
[11] And through thy knowledge shall the weak brother perish, for whom Christ died? [
12] But when ye sin so against the brethren, and wound their weak conscience, ye sin against Christ
[13] Wherefore, if meat make my brother to offend, I will eat no flesh while the world standeth, lest I make my brother to offend.

Jesus did not come to the world to die for himself. He came for you and me. He denied himself of his glory coming to the world and working around touching lives. He became poor so we can be rich. He did everything for the souls of men.

My brethren, if we are saved, it is not only for you. You are saved to rise up for others. So you are not to be concerned about only your comfort . Think about others who are looking up to you. Wearing of trousers or not is not actually the issue because many born again sisters are wearing other things more terrible than trousers because according to them, they love to be comfortable.

There are some terrible trousers people wear these days that reveal all the shape and contour of their bodies same with very tight and mini skirts.

Where is the love of God in us if our intention is to cause others to fall?
You may not know but that is the target of the enemy.

We were coming from outside the country some times ago, and at the airport I saw a married lady with her child and husband following. She wore a very tight pair of jeans trousers which exposed her in a very seductive way . It was too tight that it is difficult to explain. Such a lady is married, but to her she just wanted to wear something she loved to wear, without considering the impact on others. That is not love.

A Christian has liberty in Christ, but the Word of God cautions us to be careful how we use this Liberty. So we wonâ€™t make somebody to stumble away from faith.

There so many young converts who are not so strong in faith like you are. If you allow any of them to fall out of faith because of your comfort, God will not take it lightly with you.
Mark 9:42 KJVS

[42] And whosoever shall offend one of these little ones that believe in me, it is better for him that a millstone were hanged about his neck, and he were cast into the sea.

A sister was telling me why she decided not wear trousers again. She and her friend went for evangelism her friend wore trousers and blouse while she wore a dress. She used to wear trousers too due to the nature of her work. So many times she is in trousers even when she is not in her place of work. She is so much used to wearing trousers. Fortunately for her that day she didnâ€™t put on trousers and so they were out for evangelism.

They now met a man and started preaching to him. She said the man was just looking at her friend who wore trouser without paying attention to what they were saying . When he could no longer stand it he called this sister and told her to please tell her friend that wore trousers to excuse them. The man said he could not imagine somebody like her preaching to him. That was how the friend left them and the man now told the sister to continue the massage, that he can now listen. This incidence affected the sister that when she got back home. She gave out all her trousers. There is nothing bad in wearing trousers especially when it necessary like in some profession, activities and so on. And everybody will understand.

The most important thing for you to know as a child of God is that you are not living for yourself only, but for the Lord and the people you will reach for Christ. If the holy spirit is actually living in you ,you will be concerned how you treat your body to glorify God.

If such sisters were to be in the western world, nobody would read any meaning to it because they see nothing special in you wearing trousers since it is part of their life style. But it means different thing to a lot of people in Africa.

It is not spiritually wise to bring their ways of life here. It may hinder the move of God. We therefore need to listen to our spirits on how to dress. That body belongs to God and everything God would do in this world is through that body. We therefore need to treat our body with the wisdom of God so we wonâ€™t hinder His move.

Another female minister of God was invited to a woman program. As she was dressing up to go for the program ,she heard it deep down in her from the Holy Spirit to remove her earring because she uses them. She was so confused because she has never been condemned on that before.

Anyway to have peace she had to obey her spirit. She removed it and went for the program. She was welcomed and led straight to the altar to minister. She said as she told the women â€œlet Us prayâ€ and all the women closed their eyes, The HolySpirit told her to wait, open her eyes and look at all the women seated. So she paused and opened her eyes to look at all the women in the hall. She discovered that none of them wore earrings. The the Lord told her, If she had come here with her earnings, she would not be allowed to preach because there they donâ€™t use it at all.
She was shocked and because of that she chose not to put it on again.

What am I saying therefore is that if you are a child of God, there will be sacrifices in carrying your cross to follow the Lord however little. But many believers are not ready to sacrifice anything, and for such, you donâ€™t expect God to use you beyond your church.

If you want God to trust you with great work ,you must be ready to sacrifice your comfort at times for God to have his way in your life. There are things he may ask you to drop even though they are not sinful, but for Him to move unhindered, You may need to do so and every obedience like that will lead to promotion. So in anything we do let us know that we are not only living for ourselves but for God and souls. Do not be a stumbling blocking to others in what ever you allow in your life ,be it in your dressing ,or in any other areas of your life . That is how to walk in love. Listen to the HolySpirit because he lives in you and be ready to obey him because God is more concerned with souls of men hence he said

Mark 9:42 KJVS
[42] And whosoever shall offend one of these little ones that believe in me, it is better for him that a millstone were hanged about his neck, and he were cast into the sea.

[9/8/25, 1:04:20â€¯PM] Ahunna Theresaâ¤ï¸: Reply from the email sent to CLA: Hello Ahunna,
 
I am sorry to hear that you are in this situation.  Scholarship America is not able to issue the check directly to the student. Youâ€™ll need to work with your schoolâ€™s financial aid office in regards to the funds. 
 

Unfortunately, since colleges set their own displacement policies, we cannot provide an easy, single answer to the issue. However, there are some avenues that can be explored:

 

Â· If your school is displacing your scholarship because you have more aid than you need (an overaward), speak with a financial aid advisor about ways to restructure your aid package. You may need to file a formal appeal to do so.

Â· We may be able to defer some of your award until a subsequent year, or to use the funds for room, board or living expenses, which institutional aid doesnâ€™t typically cover. In addition, we encourage you to watch this news segment on displacement featuring retired Scholarship America CEO Robert C. Ballard (https://scholarshipamerica.org/blog/scholarship-america-on-kare-11-and-the-wall-street-journal/), and to read this tip sheet (https://scholarshipamerica.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/NSPA-on-Scholarship-Displacement.pdf) from the National Scholarship Providersâ€™ Association on more ways to deal with displacement, keeping in mind that not all of the suggestions may apply to your situation.
